I have introduced NgRx into 4 different Angular projects. Twice it was the right call. Twice it was a mistake we paid for over two years. Here is exactly how I decide now.

A few years ago, the answer to “how should I manage state in Angular?” was simple: use NgRx for anything serious. That advice made sense in an Angular without Signals, where RxJS was the only reactive primitive available and every state management approach eventually reinvented some version of actions, reducers, and subscriptions anyway.
Angular Signals changed the calculation completely. You can now build reactive, scalable state management with zero third-party libraries. You can also reach for NgRx Signal Store — a lightweight, signals-first alternative. Or you can use classic NgRx when you genuinely need its guarantees.
The problem is that most teams still default to whatever they used last time, without re-evaluating against the actual requirements of the current project. I have watched teams write actions, reducers, and effects for a five-field shopping cart. I have also watched teams build a shared-state nightmare with plain services because nobody set boundaries early.
This article is the framework I now use before writing a single line of state management code — built from the two times I got it right and the two times I got it expensively wrong.

The Three Options, Briefly
Before the framework, here is what each option actually looks like in code, using the same example throughout: a shopping cart with add, remove, update quantity, and a computed total.
Option 1 — Plain Signals (No Library)
// cart.store.ts — zero dependencies beyond @angular/core
import { Injectable, signal, computed } from '@angular/core';export interface CartItem {
productId: number;
name: string;
price: number;
quantity: number;
}@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CartStore {
// State — a single signal holding the array
private readonly items = signal<CartItem[]>([]); // Expose as readonly for consumers
readonly cartItems = this.items.asReadonly(); // Computed — derived state, automatically memoized
readonly totalPrice = computed(() =>
this.items().reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price * item.quantity, 0)
); readonly totalItems = computed(() =>
this.items().reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.quantity, 0)
); readonly isEmpty = computed(() => this.items().length === 0); // Methods — the only way to mutate state
addToCart(item: CartItem): void {
this.items.update(current => {
const existing = current.find(i => i.productId === item.productId);
if (existing) {
return current.map(i =>
i.productId === item.productId
? { ...i, quantity: i.quantity + item.quantity }
: i
);
}
return [...current, item];
});
} removeFromCart(productId: number): void {
this.items.update(current => current.filter(i => i.productId !== productId));
} updateQuantity(productId: number, quantity: number): void {
this.items.update(current =>
current.map(i => i.productId === productId ? { ...i, quantity } : i)
);
} clearCart(): void {
this.items.set([]);
}
}// In a component — read directly, no subscriptions
@Component({ changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush })
export class CartSummaryComponent {
private cartStore = inject(CartStore); items = this.cartStore.cartItems;
total = this.cartStore.totalPrice;
itemCount = this.cartStore.totalItems;
}This is genuinely all you need for a large class of Angular applications. No actions, no reducers, no dispatch, no boilerplate beyond the store itself.
Option 2 — NgRx Signal Store
// cart.store.ts — structure without the ceremony
import { computed, inject } from '@angular/core';
import { signalStore, withState, withComputed, withMethods, patchState } from '@ngrx/signals';
import { rxMethod } from '@ngrx/signals/rxjs-interop';
import { pipe, switchMap, tap } from 'rxjs';interface CartState {
items: CartItem[];
loading: boolean;
}const initialState: CartState = { items: [], loading: false };export const CartStore = signalStore(
{ providedIn: 'root' }, // 1. State — each property automatically becomes a Signal
withState(initialState), // 2. Derived state — computed Signals
withComputed(({ items }) => ({
totalPrice: computed(() =>
items().reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price * item.quantity, 0)
),
totalItems: computed(() =>
items().reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.quantity, 0)
),
})), // 3. Methods — including async side effects via rxMethod
withMethods((store, cartService = inject(CartApiService)) => ({
addToCart(item: CartItem) {
patchState(store, (state) => {
const existing = state.items.find(i => i.productId === item.productId);
const items = existing
? state.items.map(i =>
i.productId === item.productId
? { ...i, quantity: i.quantity + item.quantity }
: i)
: [...state.items, item];
return { items };
});
}, removeFromCart(productId: number) {
patchState(store, (state) => ({
items: state.items.filter(i => i.productId !== productId)
}));
}, // Async side effect — co-located with the rest of the store
syncWithServer: rxMethod<void>(
pipe(
tap(() => patchState(store, { loading: true })),
switchMap(() => cartService.saveCart(store.items())),
tap(() => patchState(store, { loading: false }))
)
),
}))
);// In a component — inject and use directly
@Component({ changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush })
export class CartSummaryComponent {
readonly cartStore = inject(CartStore);
// Template reads: cartStore.totalPrice(), cartStore.items(), cartStore.loading()
}NgRx Signal Store gives you a consistent shape across the team — withState, withComputed, withMethods — without requiring actions, reducers, or effects files. rxMethod lets you co-locate async operations (like an API call) directly in the store, instead of scattering them across services and effects.
Option 3 — Classic NgRx
// cart.actions.ts
export const addToCart = createAction(
'[Cart] Add Item',
props<{ item: CartItem }>()
);
export const removeFromCart = createAction(
'[Cart] Remove Item',
props<{ productId: number }>()
);
export const syncCartSuccess = createAction('[Cart] Sync Success');
export const syncCartFailure = createAction(
'[Cart] Sync Failure',
props<{ error: string }>()
);// cart.reducer.ts
export const cartReducer = createReducer(
initialState,
on(addToCart, (state, { item }) => {
const existing = state.items.find(i => i.productId === item.productId);
const items = existing
? state.items.map(i =>
i.productId === item.productId
? { ...i, quantity: i.quantity + item.quantity }
: i)
: [...state.items, item];
return { ...state, items };
}),
on(removeFromCart, (state, { productId }) => ({
...state,
items: state.items.filter(i => i.productId !== productId)
}))
);// cart.selectors.ts
export const selectCartItems = (state: AppState) => state.cart.items;
export const selectTotalPrice = createSelector(
selectCartItems,
(items) => items.reduce((sum, item) => sum + item.price * item.quantity, 0)
);// cart.effects.ts
@Injectable()
export class CartEffects {
private actions$ = inject(Actions);
private cartService = inject(CartApiService); syncCart$ = createEffect(() =>
this.actions$.pipe(
ofType(addToCart, removeFromCart),
switchMap(() => this.cartService.saveCart().pipe(
map(() => syncCartSuccess()),
catchError(error => of(syncCartFailure({ error })))
))
)
);
}// In a component
@Component({ changeDetection: ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush })
export class CartSummaryComponent {
private store = inject(Store); totalPrice = this.store.selectSignal(selectTotalPrice); addItem(item: CartItem) {
this.store.dispatch(addToCart({ item }));
}
}Same requirements. Four files instead of one. Significantly more boilerplate — but also significantly more structure, traceability, and tooling support.

The Decision Framework
Here is the framework I now apply before writing any state management code. I ask these questions in order and stop at the first one that gives a clear answer.
Question 1 — Is this state local to one component or shared?
If the state lives entirely within one component and its direct children, you do not need any of the above. A plain signal() and computed() inside the component is correct. This is the most common state management mistake I see — reaching for a service-level store for state that one component owns completely.
Question 2 — Is this state shared across 2–5 components within one feature?
This is the sweet spot for plain Signal services. A single @Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' }) class with signals, computed values, and methods. No library needed. This covers the majority of real-world Angular applications — shopping carts, user preference panels, form wizards, notification systems.
The failure mode to avoid here: do not let a plain Signal service grow into an unstructured mess. Keep one store per feature. If a single store file exceeds roughly 150 lines or starts handling unrelated concerns, that is the signal to add structure — which leads to the next question.
Question 3 — Does the state involve complex async orchestration, but the team is comfortable with Signals?
This is where NgRx Signal Store earns its place. You get the benefits of consistent structure — every store looks the same across the codebase, withState/withComputed/withMethods is instantly recognisable to any Angular developer who has seen it once — without the action/reducer/effect ceremony.
rxMethod is the key feature that tips me toward Signal Store over plain Signals: when a piece of state needs debouncing, retries, or cancellation logic (the RxJS operator toolkit), Signal Store gives you a clean place to put that logic, co-located with the state it updates.
Question 4 — Does the application need a strict audit trail, time-travel debugging, or enforced unidirectional flow across a large team?
This is the only scenario where classic NgRx is still the right default in 2026. Specifically:

• Regulatory or compliance requirements where every state change needs to be traceable to a specific named action, for audit purposes.

• Large teams (10+ developers) where the strict separation of actions, reducers, selectors, and effects prevents architectural drift — anyone can predict where any piece of logic lives.

• Complex async flows — sagas, chained effects, cross-feature side effects that need explicit, named coordination points.

• DevTools-dependent debugging culture — if your team relies heavily on Redux DevTools to debug production issues by replaying action sequences, that workflow is hard to replicate with Signal Store or plain Signals.
If none of these apply, classic NgRx is very likely overkill, and the boilerplate cost will not be justified by a corresponding benefit.

The Quick-Reference Table
ScenarioRecommended ApproachState local to one componentsignal() + computed() directly in the componentShared across 2–5 components, one featurePlain Signal serviceShared across a feature, needs async orchestrationNgRx Signal Store + rxMethodCross-cutting state used by 10+ componentsNgRx Signal Store, feature-scopedRegulatory audit trail requiredClassic NgRxLarge team (10+ devs), strict architecture neededClassic NgRxTime-travel debugging is part of your workflowClassic NgRxMigrating an existing classic NgRx app incrementallyNgRx Signal Store, feature by feature

The Two Times I Got It Wrong
Mistake 1 — Introducing classic NgRx for a 3-developer project with simple state.
Early in my use of NgRx, I introduced it for a project with three developers and state that was, in retrospect, almost entirely feature-local. We had actions, reducers, selectors, and effects for state that never needed cross-feature coordination. Every new feature required four new files before any actual business logic was written. Onboarding a new developer took noticeably longer because they had to learn the NgRx mental model before they could ship anything. Eighteen months later, we quietly migrated most of it to plain services — the audit trail and time-travel debugging we thought we needed were never actuall
